column168: As freight was being unloaded at destination terminal, the tote was discovered leaking on the dock. Investigation revealed that the plastic body of the tote was punctured by a piece of protruding wood on another skid. The hole in the tote was immediately patched to prevent further release. The released product on the dock floor was neutralized and cleaned up with absorbent material and containerized to be disposed of. A cleanup contractor was called to the scene to transfer the contents of the liquid and disposed of the damaged tote. Therefore, the package specifications were unable to be obtained.
column169: This incident was caused by a piece of a broken skid that may have been pushed up against the tote. This incident may be used in future dock safety topics to illustrate the importance of placing proper dunnage.

SequenceEvent: The package was found to be damaged after being taken off the belt as the powder inside could be heard moving throughout the box. It was brought to the attention of QA, and personal protective equipment was used to transport it to the hazmat cage where it would be processed. DescribePack: The external packaging was a fiberboard box that was taped and undamaged, however upon inspection it was found that the inner contents were damaged as a result of a lack of inner packaging. The plastic pail inside had a loose cap which spilled it's contents inside the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The package was placed in a hazardous materials tote box and after being processed, was sealed in a hazardous materials bag inside a sealed salvage drum.

SequenceEvent: After being brought over to QA to be processed, the package leaked corrosive liquid onto 4 other packages. All 5 packages were then placed in seperate hazardous materials totes for each one, and brought over to the hazmat cage with the use of personal protective equipment. The 4 packages that were spilled onto were found to be undamaged. Their tracking numbers are 236361381732151, 236361381732175, 236361381735619, 236361381726396. All of the hazardous materials involved were properly sealed in seperate salvage drums. DescribePack: The package was a fiberboard box containing 4 bottles of corrosive liquid. One of the bottles had a loose cap which resulted in it's contents spilling out. The release extended towards other packages, which lead to them all being repacked in drums. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: In order to mitigate the release, all of the affected packages were brought to the hazardous materials cage in separated red hazmat tote containers. The damaged portion of the affected package containers have all been cut off and added to the damaged hazmat package and bottles of corrosive liquid inside of a hazardous materials bag inside a sealed salvage drum. Personal protective equipment was used to transport and properly seal the damaged product. Absorbing material was used to clean up the area of the spill, and all of the undamaged hazardous materials were sealed in separate salvage drums before being labelled properly and sent out for delivery.

One of the bottles had a loose cap which resulted in it's contents spilling out. The release extended towards other packages, which lead to them all being repacked in drums. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: In order to mitigate the release, all of the affected packages were brought to the hazardous materials cage in separated red hazmat tote containers. The damaged portion of the affected package containers have all been cut off and added to the damaged hazmat package and bottles of corrosive liquid inside of a hazardous materials bag inside a sealed salvage drum. Personal protective equipment was used to transport and properly seal the damaged product. Absorbing material was used to clean up the area of the spill, and all of the undamaged hazardous materials were sealed in separate salvage drums before being labelled properly and sent out for delivery.

Rail car RCRX 2168 containing Hydrochloric Acid residue arrived in Paducah Yard via CN interchange on 12/1/2021 at 1442 hours.  The car had not been touched or switched yet by P&L switch crews, but was observed venting by an on duty switch crew (RS2P-01) at the north end of Paducah Yard at approximately 1744 hours.  Chemtrec, NRC, and all other notifications were made.  The car was moving to be stored per an agreement with Reagent in Paducah Yard, but had not been placed to storage at the time.  E3 was notified and responded to mitigate the leak.  This was primarily a vapor release only with a very small amount of product forming around the leak points likely from condensation.  E3 reported that 8 of 8 bolts on what they called the "unloading valave" were not even hand tight, as well as 4 out of 4 bolts being loose on the PRD.  When those bolts were tightened the leak stopped with no need for replacement or repair of any parts.  All gaskets and PRD device found to be in good working order and serviceable.
column169: Improve inspection procedures at shipper to ensure cars are properly packaged and sealed prior to shipment.  If the car was not venting when picked up by CN from the shipper the Conductor likely would not have noticed the lack of securement on top.

column168: At 12:26 EST - ERTS was contacted by ESTES regarding a 50 gallon spill of Sodium Hydroxide Solution (UN1824) from a 55 gallon poly drum on a trailer #298226. The spill has impacted the trailer floor and asphalt underneath. ERTS dispatched HEPACO to conduct all onsite cleanup operations. At 1545 ET, HEPACO arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately 50-gallons of product released to a 10'x8' area inside the trailer and 40'x40' outside the trailer. HEPACO placed the drum on its side to prevent further release. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into (4) 55-gallon metal drums. The damaged drum and product was placed into (2) 65-gallon poly drum overpack. All waste was staged on site for terminal personnel to manage.

On 12-9-21 at 1200 personnel in the CSXT Moncrief Yard discovered WCHX23122, a loaded tank  car of Crude Sulfate Turpentine leaking vapors from the manway. The car was isolated and Georgia  Pacific, and Chemtrec were notified Chemtrec Report 2021-12-09-00197. Joshua Dearing, a CSXT  hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found 1 of 6 manway swing bolt  not applied. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Tom  Davidson 251-809-7358.The vapor release from the manway was corrected.  A new manway  gasket was installed and rust scale build up on the lid of the manway was removed to help with  a better seal and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching  move.

RCRX 1496 was a residue Hydrochloric Acid rail car moving to Paducah Yard for storage per an agreemnet with Reagent.  The car arrived in Paducah Yard at 1728 hours on 12/2/2021 via the CN interchange.  At 1957 hours on 12/2/2021 during inbound inspection the car man on duty reported the car venting.  E3 was called to inspect and make repairs.  E3 reported bolts that had worked loose and fell out on top of the car at what they called the "unloading valve."  (Photos attached).  The bolts found loose and out of place were replaced and secured which stopped the leak.  All gaskets were in good working order and serviceable.  The only cause of the leak was lack of securement of the bolts.

All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 0001 ET, XPO Logistics notified ERTS of a cargo release at XNW. It was reported that 1 gallon of UN3266 “Formula 305” released from a 5 gallon plastic jug due to a forklift accident. The release occurred on the trailer. ERTS dispatched Miller Environmental to conduct all onsite cleanup activities. At 0315 EST, Miller personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2 gallons of product released to a 10' x 1' area of the trailer floor and impacted other freight. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into a 35 gallon poly drum along with Formula 305 pails. Other impacted freight that did not release was then collected into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 2 PLASTIC 5 LITER JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/2 ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 10 OZ OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTONS. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A 2 BOXED (INTERNAL ONE NON-CORRUGATED) CONFIGURATION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX RATED AT 200 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: SequenceEvent: During the day sort, a wet hazmat arrived at the hazmat cage at around 11:30 AM. Contents were immediately inspected and upon inspection, 1 of 4 bottles containing Ecolab Lime-A-Way was found crushed causing internal leakage. Contents were then immediately placed inside of a yellow salvage drum inside of a clear hazmat bag to stop the leakage from from spreading. DescribePack: Upon inspecting the damaged hazmat, 1 of 4 bottles was found crushed causing internal leakage. Half of the bottle was crushed and the damages that were made were most likely from it getting dropped during the loading process. Also, no inner packaging was found to protect the contents inside of the package. DurationRel: 3 and MitigateEffect: Upon discovering the damaged hazmat, contents were immediately placed inside of a salvage drum to minimize anymore leakage. Any spillage that came to be was immediately cleaned up.

DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Box was removed from other workers and put into a red tote along with a HazMat bag.  It was then put into the HazMat cage.

SequenceEvent: The package was found on the belt where it was leaking onto two other packages, one of which was containing corrosive liquid as well. All of the affected packages were placed in totes and brought to the attention of QA. Personal protective equipment was used to transport it to the hazmat cage. The tracking ids for the additional packages are 555119076430 and 287219886167. DescribePack: The package was a fiberboard box with no inner packaging containing 4 bottles of liquid detergent. One of the bottles had a loose cap and leaked through the package onto two other packages. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The packages were all contained in hazardous material totes and absorbent material was used to clean up the spill. The packages were brought over to the hazmat cage using personal protective equipment, and after being processed, all the damaged product were sealed within salvage drums.

Trailer containing waste was delivered from Borger, TX to the Dallas, TX location approximately 10 pm on 12/16/21.  The trailer was staged at the loading dock till morning.  First shift employees offloading inbound trucks on the main warehouse shipping dock noticed a strong odor of something burning.  After further investigation, employees noticed smoke billowing out from one of the drooped STO inbound trailers.  The fire alarm was pulled and the fire department contacted.  Employees and visitors quickly evacuated the facility and gathered at the rally point for a head count.  Local FD arrived, putting fire out.  Once fire was out and inspection saw a pallet of lead acid batteries stored on a wood pallet had burned/melted and damaged other pallets on the truck.  The lead acid batteries were stored on their side, stacked 3-5 high on multiple pallets.  The battery leads were not covered or taped.  The working assumption is a battery leaked and the pallet caught fire.    A third party clean up company via CURA came in the repackage the batteries and other containers that received damage.  The costs are unknown at this time.

column168: On 12/1/21, RNLU100129 (waybill declared Hazmat    UN1791) was reported leaking after deramping in the BNSF Stockton hub & was moved to the containment pit. US Ecology was dispatched for inspection & remediation, along with notification to Premium Env. Services. The release is approx. 20 drops per minute with a current release in the pit of 2 gals. US Ecology   s 1st responder reports pH as 13    Caustic which currently fits the declared product    bleach. Root cause was a pallet was loaded into the side of an IBC tote, cracking the liner releasing approx. 200 gallons of the Sodium Hypochlorite solution (Justeq07) during transit from Chicago to Stockton. The remaining quantity (~100 gals) was transferred into drums for manifesting.
column169: Inspect to ensure your equipment is in acceptable condition & remind everyone to secure all cargo properly per BNSF requirements. column168: While inspecting a shipment of drums, a drum of class 9 semisolid material was discovered to have a pinhole leak that released 16oz of liquid onto ground. The leaking drum was immediately overpacked to contain the release. Once overpacked, Veolia reassessed the situation thoroughly by reviewing the waste information profile sheet.  It was determined that the material may have corrosive characteristics based on the physical description of the material and associated EPA codes which could lead to further packaging complications.  Testing of the spilled liquid showed a PH of 2, so it is considered to be a corrosive material which could corrode metal drums. Upon further inspection, Veolia identified 4 additional drums slowly failing as well. At that point, Veolia decided to overpack all 12 drums in the shipment as an additional precaution to prevent a release while in transportation.
column169: Remind the customer that waste material that has corrosive properties should not be packed in metal packagings. Veolia field technicians were reminded to check for compatibility of the hazardous waste with the packaging prior to picking up and transporting the shipment.

column168: SequenceEvent: A driver was removing packages from his van when he discovered the box was a little damp on the bottom. Our coworker who does the hazmat shipping was near him and he asked her which she immediately placed in a bag and a hazmat bucket and brought it to my attention to inspect. The driver told her no package was near the hazmat and when checking the floor it was not damp. DescribePack: When I opened it up to inspect, I notice the box didn't have enough packing material inside and one of the bottles the top was pushed in and had a crack in the side where it was pushed in. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: When I was handed the package to inspect, I brought it to the hazmat cage with the air flow fan on to make sure nothing was released.

SequenceEvent: Hazmat Package was found by QA container wet. DescribePack: 4 1 Gallon bottles of 70% isopropyl Alcohol had internal leakage due to loose caps. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package and all contents were immediately placed into a Salvage Drum.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE CAME TO QA WET. UPON CLOSER INSPECTION FOUND THAT THE PLASTIC JERRICAN INSIDE THE BOX LEAKED FROM CAP. BOX LEADED ON SIDE AT PREVIOUS LOCATION. ALL EXCESS LIQUID ABSORBED BY THE BOX. BOX DRUMMED AND SENT TO THE HAZMAT CAGE. DescribePack: LOOSE CAP DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: BOX WAS PUT IN A TOTE AND BROUGHT TO QA.

SequenceEvent: Driver picked up the pkg from the shipper and upon returning to the facility there was visible leakage from the package on the box. Inspection was performed and the contents were put into a hazmat safe drum and secured. It was discovered that 1 of the 4 caps to the bottles was loose and leaked into the package. No other bottle top was loose. DescribePack: The cap was not securely tightened onto the bottles inside the package. This caused leakage as soon as the package was not upright. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Items inside the box were turned upright to stop the spillage and the package was placed in a hazmat drum and secured. Further processing followed.

column168: On 12/3/2021 at 1745 hrs, CN transportation was switching on the south end of CN Geismar yard, Geismar, La.  While switching GATX 76227 (load / UN 2784 Amines, Liquid, Corrosive, Flammable, (3-AMINOPROPYLDIMETHYLAMI NE) CLASS 8//(3)//PG II ), into track 12.  When the railcar coupled into stationary railcars in the track, liquid was observed coming from the safety relief device.  The railcar was isolated.  All required notifications were made.  CN response team responded.  Upon closer inspection, liquid was observed in the SRV and on top of the railcar.  The pressure on the railcar was checked and found to be at 0 psi.  The shipper was contacted and they advised that when they secured the railcar, it was at 0 psi.  The SRV was determined to have released early.  The railcar is being held for the shipper to make corrective action.

SequenceEvent: At 5:20 I walked the dock while our preparations were being made to start our sort. I saw on the 200 Belt section at 5:30 that there was a Hazmat that was damaged and had writing from the driver that it was damaged with an arrow pointing to the leak. I quickly looked for PPE and once I was wearing them I put the damaged hazmat into a salvage drum and isolated it near our QA station. I promptly called the emergency contact information and informed upper management of the spill. DescribePack: The box is around 12x12x12 Inches, the upper left corner had signs of a leak and crystallization from the contents. Upon inspection found that there was a minimal leak from a loose cap. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Management isolated area and quickly gathered PPE to contain the box

column168: SequenceEvent: Was training an admin in hazmat processing in our hazmat area in QA. After processing a hazmat and we moved to the next, I found this inside a bin, upside down, and the top that was face down, was soaked in the contents liquids on the corner where the cap was inside. I then pulled the damaged hazmat over and opened it up to assess the damage. After the problem was identified, I placed it inside a salvage drum and began to conduct the damaged hazmat reporting procedure. DescribePack: Cap of the drum was wet all around. No sign of leakage when tested but cap and seams around the cap were soaked all around. (Extra note. Package was found upside down). No dents, scratches or sign of traumatic damage found to cause leak. DurationRel: 12 and MitigateEffect: Placed in a salvage drum after found by hazmat trained admin.

SequenceEvent: Box found leaking, bagged and taken to Hazmat for processing DescribePack: 1-1gallon lid leaked causing damage/leakage into box DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Box was discovered wet, bagged and taken to hazmat for processing

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: SequenceEvent: Package was discovered as being damaged by another Operations Admin. Package was wet and was sitting on the dock on the 100 Belt line at truck #137. Upon being notified, I immediately grabbed the SDS for the package and the ERG. I then assessed the package, and moved it, upon confirmation that it was safe to do so, to the Hazmat Cage to limit exposure. DescribePack: Each bottle in the box had their own plastic bag and zip tie to keep the bag shut. All four bottles were leaking due to either puncture wounds or loose caps, and one of the four bottles' plastic bag was open. The bottom of the box was soaking wet and was failing structurally because of the leakage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was moved to a well-ventilated area away from non-essential personnel and upon completion of paperwork was sealed in a drum to reduce risk of exposure while waiting for disposition.

SequenceEvent: Found by the hazmat cage. Missing a cap and contents leaking. Placed in a bad and tote, DescribePack: Loose/ missing caps. Contents leaked. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Bag and tote.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: SequenceEvent: BOX WAS DISCOVERED IN THE BELLY BY PH. NOTICED BLACK SUBSTANCE ON THE BOTTOM OF BOX. INFORMED MANAGER. MANAGER CALLED HAZMAT SPECIALIST. BOX WAS BAGGED AND CARRIED TO HWPA. SUBSTANCE WAS WIPED UP. DescribePack: BOX WAS SEVERELY COMPROMISED. THE BOTTOM AND ONE SIDE WERE COMPLETELY OPENED. THE BLACK SUBSTANCE COVERED THE INSIDE OF THE BOX, EXPOSING THE BOTTLES TO IT'S CORROSIVE PROPERTIES. THE LABELS ON ALL FOUR BOTTLES WAS COVERED IN THE SUBSTANCE AND DAMAGED. ONE OF THE BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP THAT ALLOWED THE LIQUID TO ESCAPE AND DAMAGE THE BOX AND CONTENTS. THERE WERE NO OTHER HOLES, CRACKS OR PUNCTURE MARKS TO BE NOTED. DurationRel: 10 and MitigateEffect: THE BOTTLES WERE ALL SEALED IN A HAZMAT BAG. THAT BAG WAS PLACED IN A LINED SALVAGE DRUM AND PREPARED FOR TRANSPORT TO THE HUB FOR EVALUATION.

column168: On December 28, 2021, R+L Carriers (RLC) personnel were making delivery at the above-referenced location when one (1) 275-gallon tote containing sodium hydroxide was dropped and damaged. As a result, approximately five (5) gallons of product released to the concrete loading area. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from US Ecology (USE) to perform the corrective action. Prior to USE's arrival, on-site personnel remediated the release and repaired the damaged tote to the satisfaction of the customer.

On December 28, 2021, one (1) fiberboard box containing bottles of corrosive liquid (acetic acid and nitric acid solution) was discovered damaged by R+L Carriers (RLC) at the above-referenced location. As a result of the damage, one (1) of the inner bottles of product released approximately four (4) liters to the adjacent palletized cargo. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from Alpha-Omega Training and Compliance (AOTC) to perform the necessary corrective action. AOTC personnel collected and containerized all damaged and impacted cargo into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

column168: SOTX 1889 was reported leaking from the manway area on Dec 6, 2021 at approximately 2220 hours at the PTRA Manchester Yard.  Slick Response was notified to respond to the scene and inspect the tank car. Slick Personnel found five of eight manway bolts were less than tool tight allowing product to bypass the manway lid and gasket when the car was moved.  Slick Response inspected the gasket, closed and secured the manway to tool tight specifications and cleaned the tank car exterior. It is estimated that one gallon of product leaked/sloshed from the tank car. CHEMTREC was notified, 2021120700213, and the shipper and consignee were contacted concerning the event.

column168: A Veolia employee was unloading a tote at the Dayton 10-day intransit facility from a tandem box truck. This particular truck relies on the air bags of the tandems to support the weight in the back of the truck. The Veolia employee drove a fork lift onto the back of the truck to pick up a tote. After picking up the tote our employee tried to back into the warehouse. As the forklift drove back onto the dock plate the truck sank below the dock level. This put the forklift at an odd downward angle. To account for this angle the driver had to elevate the forks a little higher than he normally would.     As the employee was exiting the truck with the tote on the forklift, a combination of the liquid inside the tote sloshing around and the bumps from the tires hitting the dock plate caused the tote to slide on the forks. The employee tried to prevent this from occurring by manipulating the controls on the forklift. As the employee quickly reached for the controls we believe he may have tilted the forks in the wrong direction causing the tote to continue its slide off of the forks. The tote eventually fell from the forks and landed on its side.    Based on the employee statement and a review of the incident, it is believed the tote lacked any kind of bottom deckboard-type component to prevent the tote from tipping from the forks. The bottom deckboard components act as a cross bar which holds the tote onto the forks. With out these cross bars the tote was free to slide or bounce as the employee drove into the warehouse.    Due to the condition of the tote after tipping over it was determined that the material needed to be pumped into an undamaged tote for safe transport. This transfer was completed by a third party ER team.
column169: 1. The Veolia office in Dayton will no longer use forklifts for removing totes from a box truck. We will be using a pallet jack instead. This should eliminate the any potential for a reoccurrence of this incident.    2. The employee was retrained on forklift operation and safety following the incident.

column168: On 12/15/21 at 1400 ET,  Landstar contacted ERTS regarding the disposal of a UN3262 Corrosive solid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s.  Allied International Emergency arrived on site at 1545 ET,  and confirmed a 2' x 2' area of the trailer floor was affected by the release of material.  Landstar requested AIE not to continue the clean up due to the shipper requesting the material to remain as is and shipped back.  At 1705 ET, Landstar requested AIE to return the next morning to separate impacted material from the non impacted material.  AIE could not return so Hepaco was dispatched and arrived on site at 1908 ET.  There is one busted supersack, and another that is not damaged, but slightly leaning. A good amount of the bags shifted in transit. The busted one is in the way of the non damaged supersack. HEPACO moved the bags around in order to access the leaning bag and advised that the supersack that initially appeared to be just slightly leaning turned out to have a hole at the bottom of the bag. HEPACO transferred the material into a cubic yard box. The damaged sack was placed into a 55 gallon DF that will be secured on the trailer along with the the pallets containing the cubic yard boxes.

WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE EVACUATED THE AREA AND CONTACTED THE DMP. WITHIN A COUPLE OF MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS SLIGHTLY LOOSE, CAUSING APPROX. 8 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON(S). THE INNER PACKAGING CONSISTED OF A DOUBLE BOX 2 CORRUGATED CONFIGURATION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 55 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).
RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE WITH PROPER PPE, CLEANED UP SPILL USING THE DECISION TREE, TRANSPORTED PACKAGE TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

column168: ON 12/24/2021, DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION RECEIVED A CALL FROM EMPLOYEE #63970 AT THE HUB FACILITY IN MEMPHIS, REPORTING A TOXIC SPILL. THIS MULTIPLE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 45 FIBERBOARD PACKAGES, EACH CONTAINING 8 – LITER GLASS CONTAINERS. TWO OF THE GLASS INNER CONTAINERS IN ONE OF THE PACKAGES SHATTERED DUE TO MISHANDLING. THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL. THE REMAINDER OF THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SEPARATE DRUM AND AWAITS AN AMENDED SHIPPER’S DECLARATION AND COMMUNICATION FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION.

VL Trucking, Inc. (VLT) was transporting 16 totes of the material. Load locks and ratchet straps were used to secure the load. During a load shift, the metal part of a ratchet mechanism produced a hole approximately half-way up on a tote. Material was released, but the vast majority remained inside the trailer. An estimated 100 gallons was lost from the tote. VLT contracted with Environmental Management, Inc. (EMI) to provide a response and cleanup. EMI went to the site on Monday, December 20, 2021, and secured the site for the night. The following morning, Tuesday, December 21, 2021, EMI returned to site. The 15 undamaged totes were removed from the trailer and sprayed with a neutralizing material. The one (1) damaged tote had its contents, approximately 150 gallons, transferred to another tote provided by EMI. The free liquids inside the trailer were solidified with inert absorbents and these solids were placed into open-top 55-gallon drums. The tote which contained the transferred material was labeled properly. The trailer was then cleaned with the neutralizing material and the 15 undamaged totes and the one (1) tote with the transferred material or (16) totes total were reloaded and secured. All waste material was shipped off the site by EMI for proper processing and disposal.

column168: On December 29,2020, at approximately 10:05 am CST, a representative with R+L Carriers (RLC) at the above-referenced location observed three(3) 75-pound batteries that were damaged due to falling off a lift gate. As a result, approximately ten CIO) ounces of battery acid released to the trailer floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the cleanup. CES dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental, LLC(CES) to perform the necessary corrective action. FCE containerized the three(3) damaged batteries into one(1) 30-gallon drum for transport and disposal, then deployed a neutralizing agent to the free product on the trailer floor. Once neutralized, crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted trailer floor and worked them in using hand tools. All battery acid impacted material was collected and containerized in two(2) 30-gallon drums for transport and disposal. RLC personnel took possession of the generated waste for proper disposal. FCE personnel noted no further actions required on-site and crews demobilized.

column168: At 1958 hours on December 21, 2021 it was reported that Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) train MSHAR-21 derailed at MP 130 on the KCS Meridian Subdivision. Cause of the derailment is thought to be a broken wheel on SRAX 25123. A total of 17 cars derailed, including WFRX 838590, a loaded hopper car transporting hazardous waste (K061 Arc Furnace Dust). WFRX 838590 was punctured during the derailment, resulting in the lading release. Spilled lading has been cleaned up and is being managed appropriately. WFRX 838590 will be scrapped.  File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a "bulk" shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. column168: At 1958 hours on December 21, 2021 it was reported that Kansas City Southern Railway (KCS) train MSHAR-21 derailed at MP 130 on the KCS Meridian Subdivision. Cause of the derailment is thought to be a broken wheel on SRAX 25123. A total of 17 cars derailed, including OLNX 712154, a loaded tank car transporting SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION. OLNX 712154 was offered into transportation with a partially open bottom outlet valve (BOV). The bottom outlet cap reduction fitting on OLNX 712154 was sheared off, it could not contain release from the primary closure. Estimated release was 0.5 gallons. Upon discovery, the BOV was fully closed stopping the release. The spilled material was then neutralized. OLNX 712154 is scheduled for lading transfer and then will be scrapped.  File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a 'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.

column168: PVS Minibulk driver was scheduled to deliver a shipment of Sulfuric Acid 93% and Sodium Bisulfite 38% to Dart Container in Lancaster, PA. Once the driver arrived on site, he parked his truck outside and proceeded through the overhead door to the Sulfuric Acid unloading location. The driver proceed to don his Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) and hook up to the unloading location. Driver was going back and forth watching the gauging system and when the gauge reached 303 gallons for 405-gallon Sulfuric Acid tank on site approximately 10 gallons of Sulfuric Acid was released. The driver shut down and notified his supervisor.
column169: Gauging system was recalibrated and an additional secondary overflow gauge will be installed on the tank.

column168: On 10 Dec 21, Landstar notified ERTS of an unknown amount of leaking totes of Butyl Acrylate in a truck located near the Valero Gas Station on Highway 59 in Marshall, TX.  ERTS dispatched a contractor, upon arrival at the involved trailer and the tote of concern, the contractor observed a tote cover that was not property closed due to the bolt-on lid ring not being secured correctly by use of the related lock nut. 1-quart of product was estimated to have spilled and affected exterior components of the involved tote and a 1ft-by-1ft area of the trailer floor. Affected media was addressed via chemical pads and the tote cover was properly secured prior to contractor departure. On 13 Dec 21, ERTS contacted the contractor (E3), to discuss the details of waste included in this alert, which were confirmed that the chemical pads used to address this cleanup were going to be consolidated with similar E3 shop waste and properly disposed of when appropriate.
Tote damaged in transit.

On 12/24/2021, at approximately 0220, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee #575694 at the ramp facility in Orlando, reporting a battery fire incident. The package consisted of two sealed lead-acid batteries and various charging devices. During the sort process, the shipment emitted a dangerous evolution of heat and a burning odor. The local fire department was called to the scene to neutralize the heat. Evidence of charring appeared on the batteries and the other contents of the package. The batteries may ship under an exception, however it appears that the batteries did not have protective coverings over the post, making this an improperly prepared shipment. The package is being held for an FAA investigation.
